Rules for writing hamza in the Arabic script

Rules for writing hamza in the Arabic script

1 Introduction

The rules of hamza orthography in the Arabic script are quite complex. The matter is further complicated by the limitations of metal and digital typography technology. We attempt to give a comprehensive set of rules for writing hamza and some recommendations for typographers and typesetters.

2 Disclaimer

This article is based on findings from the authors research and may have errors. Any errors reported to the authors email will be greatly appreciated.

3 Scope

We treat only the orthography of Standard Arabic. The orthography of the Qurn ( ) is not discussed.

4 hamza orthography

4.1 Different ways hamza is written

hamza is written in four different ways:

  1. Seated on an alif: or
  2. Seated on an ww:
  3. Seated on an y:
  4. Unseated:

Here are some of notes about writing hamza in the above four methods:

  • When unseated hamza is followed by an alif: , the combination of hamza and alif is usually written as as a convention. Examples: mana, amn, anan. However, when the alif is a suffix or part of a suffix, or the hamza is doubled, or there is an alif before the hamza then we will write , not . Examples: ayni, sal, qirt.

  • When unseated hamza comes between two letters that are joined, then it is written above the line that joins them, for example: xaa. In this word, the y joins to the t marba .

  • When hamza is seated on alif, if it has an kasra, it is written below the alif: . Otherwise, it is written above the alif: , , .

  • When hamza is seated on y the dots of the y are no longer written. Heres how it will appear in different positions:

    Isolated End Middle Beginnning

    Note that hamza is seated on y in the middle position is different from unseated hamza between two joining letters .

So how do we know when to write hamza unseated and when seated? And how do we choose between its three different seats? There are a set of rules that we need to follow in order to correctly write hamza.

4.2 Ordered set of rules

  1. If hamza occurs in the beginning of a word:
    1. If the hamza carries a long- vowel, it is written unseated followed by an alif and written as , for example mana.
    2. If the hamza carries any other vowel, it is written seated on an alif, and is marked with the appropriated vowel mark, for example aslama, urdu, islm, mn, xia.
  2. If hamza occurs in the middle of a word:
    1. If there is a long vowel or diphthong before the hamza:
      1. If the hamza is after a long- vowel or ay diphthong, then the hamza will be written unseated. Examples:
        haya, xaa
        barna, barni, barna, barayni
        ayuhu, ayahu, ayihi, ayni, ayayni
        mauhu, maahu, maihi
      2. If the hamza is after a long- vowel or aw diphthong, then:
        1. If the hamza has an kasra it is written seated on y. Examples: sihi, awihi
        2. Otherwise, the hamza is written unseated. Examples: sahu, sni, tawam, awahu, awni, suhu, yasna
      3. If the hamza is after a long -vowel, then:
        1. If the hamza has an kasra it is written seated on y. Example: sil.
        2. If the hamza has an amma it is written seated on ww. Example: tasul.
        3. Otherwise, when the hamza has an fata, it is written unseated. Example: tasala, qirt.
    2. If the letter before the hamza has a sukn and is not ww or y (in which case rule 2.a would apply), then:
      1. If the hamza was originally at the end of the word, but a suffix has been attached to the word such that the hamza is now in the middle of the word, then the hamza will be written unseated. Examples: ibni, ibayni, buahu, buuhu, buihi. (, , , and are suffixes).
      2. Otherwise, if the hamza is originally at the middle of the word, then:
        1. If the hamza has a amma it is written seated on ww. Example: masl.
        2. If the hamza has a kasra it is written seated on y. Example: tars.
        3. If the hamza has an fata then:
          1. If it is followed by a long- vowel represented by an alif, the hamza is unseated followed by the alif and the combination is written as . Example: mir, amn.
          2. Otherwise, if there is no alif after the hamza, the hamza is written seated on alif. Examples: masala, , almara.
    3. If the hamza has a sukn, then look at the vowel mark on the letter preceding it:
      1. If the letter preceding hamza has a kasra, the hamza is written seated on y. Example: bisa.
      2. If the letter preceding hamza has a amma, the hamza is written seated on ww. Example: sulaka.
      3. If the letter preceding hamza has a fata, the hamza is written seated on alif. Example: kas.
    4. Otherwise, only if the above conditions are not satisfied, then compare the vowel marks of the hamza and the letter before it:
      1. If either vowel mark is an kasra then the hamza will be written on a y. Examples: suila, yaisa, muttakina, ras.
      2. If neither vowel mark is an kasra, and at least one of the vowel marks is a amma, then the hamza will be written on a ww. Examples: sul, rus, luayy.
      3. Otherwise, if both of the vowel marks are fatas, then:
        1. If the hamza is followed by a long- vowel represented by an alif, the hamza is written unseated. Examples: anan.
        2. Otherwise the hamza will be written on an alif. Examples: saala, ra.
      These set of rules apply even if the hamza or the previous letter is doubled. Examples raasa, yuraisu, ruisa, tafaul, yubarrina, yubarrana, sal, lal.
  3. If hamza is at the end of a word, disregard the vowel mark on it and consider only the letter before the hamza.
    1. If there is a long vowel (, , ) or a diphthong (aw, ay) before it then the hamza will be written unseated. Examples: duu, su, a, awa, aya.
    2. Otherwise, if the previous letter has a sukn, the hamza will again be unseated. Examples: buu, ibu, au
    3. Otherwise, if the previous letter is a doubled ww with an amma, the hamza will again be unseated. Example tabawwuu.
    4. Otherwise, if the previous letter has an:
      1. kasra, the hamza is written seated on y. Example yuhaddiu, sayyiu.
      2. amma, the hamza is written seated on ww. Example baua.
      3. fata, the hamza is written seated on alif. Example yahdau, mubtadai.

4.3 Prefixes and suffixes

  • If hamza is in the beginning of a word, adding a prefix to the word will not alter the writing of the hamza. Examples: + = .

  • If hamza is at the end of a word, adding a suffix to the word can, in general, alter the writing of the hamza, except in cases that have already been mentioned above. Examples:

  • As we mentioned earlier, when unseated hamza is followed by an alif which is not a suffix: , the combination of hamza and alif is conventionally written as . However, if the unseated hamza is doubled or preceded by another alif then it wont be written as . Example: sal, qirt.

5 tanwn on final hamza

tanwn on a final hamza does not affect the writing of the hamza except in the case of tanwn al-fat. When writing tanwn al-fat on a hamza at the end of a word:

  1. If there is an alif before a unseated hamza , then we dont add a silent alif when writing tanwn al-fat. For example becomes dan, not .

  2. Otherwise, we add the silent alif after the hamza so that the hamza is now in the middle of the word with a suffix alif after it. We now pretend that the hamza has an fata and that the alif after it is a long- vowel. Then we go through the rules for writing hamza in the middle of a word (given above) to determine how hamza will be written. We then write the an-mark on the hamza. For example becomes mubtadaan, becomes mubtadian, becomes buan, becomes ayan.

6 Variants

There are some historical and geographical variants to the above rules. The main one is a variant of rule 2.b.ii above. In this variant, when the letter before hamza has a sukn, the hamza is generally written unseated. So they write:

However, this rule appears to not consistently be followed. For example, al-mara is generally always written never .

A second variant is to write hamza unseated when:

  1. it has a amma and is followed by a long- vowel. Example: instead of .
  2. it has a kasra and is followed by a long- vowel. Example: instead of .

7 Typographical limitations

Due to what appears to have been a limitation of typographical technology in the days of typewriters, metal typrography, and early digital typography, unseated hamza between two joining letters was usually written as seated on y instead: . Because of this limitation we are now accustommed to seeing:

  • instead of
  • instead of
  • instead of
  • instead of

and similar variants.

These variants have pervaded to such a degree that many modern treatises on the rules of hamza orthography present the above as the correct way of writing, and modify their rules with exceptions to allow this writing.

Fortunately, advancements in digital typography technology now allow us to revert back to the original rules. However, unfortunately, only very few computer fonts today actually implement this feature.

Two fonts, of which we are aware, that do allow the preferred orthography are:

  1. Dr Khaled Hosnys Amiri: https://www.amirifont.org/
  2. DecoType Naskh: https://www.decotype.com/oneliner/

With these hamza-safe fonts you can always use U+0621 Arabic Letter Hamza to type unseated hamza no matter whether it is between joining or non-joining letters. With most other fonts U+0621 Arabic Letter Hamza will prevent the surrounding two letters from joining.

We recommend that Arabic typographers implement this much needed feature as has been implemented in the two fonts mentioned above.

This issue has been discussed in detail by Thomas Milo in Unicode L2/14-109: https://unicode.org/L2/L2014/14109-inline-chars.pdf.

We may also mention that there is a way of faking the correct orthography with most fonts. This is to write a combination of U+0640 Arabic Tatweel and U+0654 Arabic hamza above thus to achieve the appearance of unseated hamza between two joining letters. However, this will not work when hamza is between lm and alif in the mandatory lam-alif ligature (correct: , incorrect: ). This may also affect the searching of characters in a digital document so we are hesitant to recommend this hack.
